-- ── Dead Man's Snitch ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Dead Man's Snitch is a cron job and scheduled task monitoring service that watches for expected check-ins from periodic jobs, such as cron tasks, Heroku Scheduler runs, or any other recurring process, and alerts a team when a job fails to report in on time. Founded in 2012 and acquired by web development studio Collective Idea in 2013, it remains a widely used, straightforward monitoring tool for developers. It offers a free single-snitch plan plus paid monthly plans that scale up the number of monitored jobs and integrations.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium subscription with a free single-job plan and paid monthly plans priced by number of monitored jobs (snitches)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free plan available for one job; paid plans start at 5 US dollars per month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2012, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Not publicly disclosed; operated as a product of Collective Idea, a small web development studio$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Holland, Michigan, United States (Collective Idea)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Dead Man's Snitch Review 2026: Pricing and Features$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Dead Man's Snitch monitors cron jobs and scheduled tasks, alerting you when they fail to run. See its pricing plans, features, and how it works.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Dead Man's Snitch, at deadmanssnitch.com, is a cron job and scheduled task monitoring service built to solve a specific, common infrastructure problem: cron jobs and other periodic tasks tend to fail silently, and teams often only discover a missed backup, report, or sync job long after the fact. The tool works on a simple check-in model, sometimes called a dead man's switch pattern: a monitored job is configured to ping a unique URL, called a snitch, at the end of a successful run, and if that ping does not arrive within an expected time window, Dead Man's Snitch fires an alert to notify the team that something went wrong, whether the job crashed, hung, or never ran at all. This approach works for any periodic process, not just traditional Unix cron jobs, including Heroku Scheduler tasks, Windows scheduled tasks, CI/CD pipeline steps, and custom background workers, since the only requirement is the ability to make an outbound HTTP request on success. The service was founded in 2012 and was acquired by Collective Idea, a web development studio based in Holland, Michigan, on July 30, 2013, and has continued to operate as one of Collective Idea's products since. Dead Man's Snitch's positioning emphasizes simplicity: rather than being a full observability or application-performance-monitoring platform, it focuses narrowly on the question of whether a scheduled job checked in when expected, making it fast to set up and easy to reason about compared to heavier monitoring suites. Pricing follows a tiered structure based primarily on the number of snitches, meaning the number of distinct monitored jobs, a customer needs. The free Lone Snitch plan covers a single monitored job, suitable for hobbyists or very small setups. Paid plans include Little Birdy at 5 US dollars per month for 3 snitches with basic check-in intervals, API access, a Field Agent feature, and unlimited team members; Private Eye at 19 US dollars per month for 100 snitches with enhanced intervals and additional integrations; and Surveillance Van at 49 US dollars per month for 300 snitches with enhanced intervals, integrations, Smart Alerts, and Error Notices, which lets the service also flag jobs that check in but report an error status rather than simply going silent. All paid tiers include API access and unlimited team members, meaning pricing scales primarily with the number of monitored jobs rather than the number of people who need access, which is a notable difference from many other developer tools that charge per seat. Customers needing on-premise hosting, higher snitch limits, or more extensive monitoring capabilities beyond the published plans are directed to contact the company directly for a custom arrangement. Integrations typically include common alerting and chat channels such as email, Slack, and other webhook-based notification targets, letting teams route missed check-in alerts into their existing incident-response workflows. As a directory entry in 2026, Dead Man's Snitch is best understood as a lightweight, focused, and long-standing cron and scheduled-job monitoring tool, well suited to teams that want a simple, reliable way to catch silently failing background jobs without adopting a full observability platform, and its per-job rather than per-seat pricing model makes it especially cost-effective for larger teams monitoring a moderate number of jobs.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '8f1f6581-f42c-4ff4-a4aa-54f0bd634a79';

